1.length <= 100\nnums2.length == nums1.length\n0 <= nums1[i], nums2[i] <= 105\nnums2 is an anagram of nums1.\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def anagramMappings(self, nums1: List[int], nums2: List[int]) -> List[int]:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom collections import defaultdict\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def anagramMappings(self, nums1: List[int], nums2: List[int]) -> List[int]:\n        mapper = defaultdict(set)\n        for i, num in enumerate(nums2):\n            mapper[num].add(i)\n        return [mapper[num].pop() for num in nums1]\n```\n\nThis solution uses a dictionary to map each element in `nums2` to the set of indices where it appears. Since `nums2` is an anagram of `nums1`, each element in `nums1` will have a corresponding index in `nums2`. The use of a set allows handling duplicates correctly, and `pop()` is used to retrieve an index from the set. This approach ensures that the solution is efficient and works correctly even when there are duplicate elements in the input arrays.", "estimated_date": 1438905600000}